I would imagine laser based weaponry would be extremely viable for ship to ship combat. A huge problem with space is heat. Cooling stuff off is significantly harder because you can’t vent heat into an atmosphere, you have to get rid of it on ship. While I’m sure combat spaceships would have shuntable heatsinks, laser combat would likely be more about heating your opponents ship up to lethal levels rather than actually damaging the ship.
At the same time a particle accelerator would be less viable for ship based combat because while it would be great at making many breaches into the ships hull, leaking any atmosphere, spacesuits are a thing. It would probably be easier to outright kill a prepared crew instead of trying to asphyxiate them. You might notice that heat resistant suits are a thing and once an atmosphere is gone the crew can just avoid the hull as much as possible, electronics and delicate machinery can’t do the same.
Heat a ship up enough and capacitors used for weaponry will burst to devastating effect on nearby electronics. Batterys and lights too.

You are right.
Actually now that I think about it particle accelerators might actually help with that. A loose spray of atoms can scour the surface of a ship easily, probably enough to deal with heat shielding.
I would imagine any large ships would rely on missiles. Space combat would likely evolve in one of a couple ways. Possibly a reliance on maneuverability to not get hit and combat being quick and brutal.
It could also end up being long range as you said, though missies would be much more suited than simple ballistics. Space is 3 dimensional to an extreme. Unlike air combat you can keep going up or down without worry and any obstructions float.
Lastly it could end up being a battle of endurance. Whose equipment is less fragile? Who can overheat the other, who has more fuel as well as more efficient use of it, who can disable more parts of an enemy ship than the other. As soon as engines die a battle is effectively over, the other ship won’t be able to maneuver and blind spots will always exist, they would be taken advantage of.
I feel like the most likely is endurance just due to the practicality of it. Ships are less likely to be outright destroyed, an obvious advantage to crews. Also ships being more durable has obvious advantages in general. Imagine a military fleet being able to plow through an asteroid field to flank an enemy at a critical moment because the ships are durable enough to do so.

>>31301044
Having experience with industrial lasers, the question is always "What kind?"
The most common for Class 4 is still CO2, but the flaw is they can't do much to most metals without a fuckton of power. You can etch the coatings off, that's it. A machine with a lower wattage meant for marking is different than a ultrahigh wattage cutting robot.
While the whole rods from god scenario is still basic physics, one thing I've never seen is casual writing is that lasers require lenses. Like many subjects, you can't know everything from a wiki.
A good lens is key to a tight beam, but has an optimal focus. And in industrial settings lenses are like underwear. It's possible to keep your mechanics perfect, but a physical lens is still subject to wear & tear.
Use a bit of rangefinding, adjust the beam focus via energy or whatever technobabble your setting has, and choose the right beam frequency.

Anonymous Sat 04 Jul 2020 20:43:22 No.31304577 Report
Quoted By: >>31305453 >>31305985
>>31301454
>>31301044
Other key point: most heat shields don't work the way people think they do.
The reason capsules are blunt objects and the shuttle bellyflopped through the upper atmosphere is that this causes the shockwave, which is where almost all of the heat is, to be pushed quite a distance forward of the surface, and there's a thick layer of significantly colder gas that's actually in contact with the heat shield. Directed heating of the surface can't really be avoided so well, and heatshielding for things like solar probes is what you would need to compare.

>>31301235
>>31301430
Other thing with lasers: every beam is a gaussian (or complex combination of multiple gaussians), no exceptions - which always diverges with a minimum size only at one point (the beam waist) whose maximum distance from your emitter is constrained by the dimensions of your optics, imposing strong range limitations when you start considering any realistic space combat distances as the beam eventually diverges to being harmlessly diffuse. This can be mitigated by using shaping optics to approximate a bessel beam, which is non-divergent, but it is always just an approximation as a true bessel emitter would need to be infinitely wide. So long as your beam is made of light, it will always end up dispersing; all you can do is find increasingly clever tricks to eke out a little bit more distance, and the mathematics has brutally diminishing returns.
This is also before considering any of the interesting effects of things like pair creation, and self-dispersion due to the Kerr effect becoming significant at higher intensities.

Anonymous Sat 04 Jul 2020 22:19:41 No.31306410 Report
Quoted By: >>31306509 >>31306665
>>31305453
this:
>>31305522
but if you want how this affects the shooty bang bang:
For very high-tech space combat settings between serious starships, lasers are capable of being extremely powerful, but only at very short range. Ship to ship they're absolute murder in close, but merely harrassing/slow attrition on your armor or shields at any normal maneuvering range. They excel as point defence weapons where the range is comparatively tiny and their unbeatable "projectile" velocity is crucial.
For low-tech settings and small scale vehicles/encounters even in high-tech, lasers, particle beams, projectiles etc. are all plausible depending on how miniaturized, lightweight or energy efficient each technology has become in your setting, and as a result which can pack the most pain into a small platform like a space shuttle sized thing, a tank, or in small arms like rifles.

>>31305975
>if you've got the capacity for interstellar travel, then you might be on the path to pour enough energy in to make a laser viable for some uses.
The big power limiter on something like a laser (or a particle beam, for that matter) is the point where the energy density of the beam causes spontaneous matter creation, which then ruins the beam. This is the thing that stops you making your laser stay effective at a great distance by just dumping in more power - the beam explodes off its own self-generated particle cloud before it even gets halfway. Which is cool as hell, but not very useful.

>>31305985

Anonymous Sun 05 Jul 2020 00:34:54 No.31308924 Report
Quoted By: >>31310346 >>31310371
>>31306509
>>spontaneous matter creation
>What the fuck?
That's literally what particle accelerators are for. If you create a massively energetic event, then any particle with a total mass energy lower than that can pop into existence using that energy provided you obey certain conservation laws (balance electric charges etc); colliding a handful of particles each travelling at a significant fraction of c into each other creates a spray of new particles in that way. Increasing the power of the accelerators increases the energy budget for producing those particles, thus making it possible to create heavier exotic particles in order to measure their properties and thus refine our models for the universe.
The LHC creates events with enough energy to instantly liquefy half a metric ton of copper, in a volume the size of a few protons (which are each only about one thousandth the width of a hydrogen atom).
Because you'll also typically get a ton of lighter particles hosing out of the collision, the total energy of the collision usually needs to be quite a bit higher than the mass-energy of the particle you hope to detect or study. Those absurdly large detectors you see in photos of things like the LHC are essentially colossal tubes of solid state detectors intended to measure the mass, charge and trajectory of the hundreds of particles spewing out from a collision: pic related is the result of a collision in one of the LHC detectors. The cylinder shape is one of those things several people tall you see in all the photos, the orange tracks are the spray of newly created particles.
If a laser beam or any other sort of field exceeds a certain energy density, same thing applies. High energy electromagnetic fields, like a super powerful laser, start to self-interact because of the spontaneous creation and destruction of electron/positron pairs.
Reality gets real fucky at high energies.
